appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no significant findings on physical examination. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of anorgasmia in males?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Use of selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors","Sexually transmitted infections","Diabetes mellitus","Prostate enlargement","Low testosterone levels"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUsage of selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely cause of anorgasmia in this patient. SSRIs, such as sertraline, are known to affect sexual function, including delayed ejaculation and anorgasmia, due to their impact on serotonin levels in the brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESexually transmitted infections\u003C/strong\u003E are less likely in this case, as the patient does not report any symptoms suggestive of an infection, such as pain or discharge, and the onset of symptoms coincides with the use of sertraline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause sexual dysfunction, however this patient does not have a history of diabetes making this option less likely. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstate enlargement\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects urinary function and may cause erectile dysfunction, but it is not commonly associated with anorgasmia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow testosterone levels\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to decreased libido and erectile dysfunction, but it is not the most common cause of anorgasmia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) are a common cause of anorgasmia in men.","Anorgasmia can be a side effect of medications such as selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs)","Considering medications and their side effects is an important aspect of managing sexual dysfunction"],"references":["Jenkins LC, Mulhall JP. Delayed orgasm and anorgasmia. Fertil Steril. 2015 Nov;104(5):1082-8. doi: 10.1016/j.fertnstert.2015.09.029. Epub 2015 Oct 9. PMID: 26439762; PMCID: PMC4816679.","Jing E, Straw-Wilson K. Sexual dysfunction in selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) and potential solutions: A narrative literature review. Ment Health Clin. 2016 Jun 29;6(4):191-196. doi: 10.9740/mhc.2016.07.191. PMID: 29955469; PMCID: PMC6007725.","Nguyen V, Dolendo I, Uloko M, Hsieh TC, Patel D. Male delayed orgasm and anorgasmia: a practical guide for sexual medicine providers. Int J Impot Res. 2024 May;36(3):186-193. doi: 10.1038/s41443-023-00692-7. Epub 2023 Apr 15. PMID: 37061617; PMCID: PMC11035123."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61730"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17744"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61730"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T14:34:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T14:34:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10458"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76226"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\